One man is saddened when his children die; another is anxious when they become ill; a third is elnbittered when they do something disgracefuL or suffer a taint in their reputation. One 1na11‚you will observe, is tortured by passion for his neighbour’s wife, another by passion for his own. You will find men who are completely upset by failure to win an election‚ and others who are actually plagued by the offices which they have won. But the largest throng of unhappy men among the host of mortals arc those whom the expectation of death, which threatens them on every hand, drives to despair. For there is no quarter from which death may not approach. Hence, like soldiers scouting in the enemy's country, they must look about in all directions, and turn their heads at every sound3 unless the breast be rid of this fear, one lives with a palpitating heart. You will readily recall those who have been driven into exile and dispossessed of their property.
